2026-06-20 | Maximum Building Height

Question
Return the maximum height of the tallest building.
	Key Insight
This is not a DP problem.
The crucial observation is:
		restrictions only matter at
		specific positions.
First make all restrictions consistent.
Then compute the highest peak possible between every pair of neighboring restrictions.
	Step 1: Add Mandatory Restriction
Since:
		building 1 = 0
Add:
		[1,0]
If building n is not restricted:
		[n,n-1]
can be added because from building 1 we can increase by at most 1 per step.
	Step 2: Sort Restrictions
Sort by building index.
	Step 3: Propagate Constraints
Left → Right
For consecutive restrictions:
		(id1,h1)
		(id2,h2)
Maximum reachable height at id2:
		h1 + (id2-id1)
So:
		h2 =
		min(h2,
		    h1 + distance)
Right → Left
Similarly:
		h1 =
		min(h1,
		    h2 + distance)
After these two passes all restrictions become feasible.
	Step 4: Find Maximum Peak
Consider two neighboring restrictions:
		(id1,h1)
		(id2,h2)
let
		d = id2-id1
The tallest achievable building between them occurs by:
		climbing up
		then descending
Maximum peak:
		(h1 + h2 + d) / 2
(integer floor)
Take maximum over all intervals.
	Approach
1.	Add mandatory restrictions.
2.	Sort restrictions.
3.	Left-to-right propagation.
4.	Right-to-left propagation.
5.	For every adjacent pair:
			peak =
			(h1+h2+d)/2
6.	Return maximum peak.
	Time Complexity
	O(m log m)
	where m = number of restrictions.
	Space Complexity
	O(m)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int maxBuilding(int n, vector<vector<int>>& restrictions) {
        restrictions.push_back({1, 0});
        sort(restrictions.begin(), restrictions.end());
        if(restrictions.back()[0] != n) {
            restrictions.push_back({n, n - 1});
        }
        int m = restrictions.size();
        for(int i = 1; i < m; i++) {
            int dist =
                restrictions[i][0] -
                restrictions[i - 1][0];
            restrictions[i][1] =
                min(restrictions[i][1],
                    restrictions[i - 1][1] + dist);
        }
        for(int i = m - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
            int dist =
                restrictions[i + 1][0] -
                restrictions[i][0];
            restrictions[i][1] =
                min(restrictions[i][1],
                    restrictions[i + 1][1] + dist);
        }
        int ans = 0;
        for(int i = 1; i < m; i++) {
            long long id1 = restrictions[i - 1][0];
            long long h1  = restrictions[i - 1][1];
            long long id2 = restrictions[i][0];
            long long h2  = restrictions[i][1];
            long long d = id2 - id1;
            long long peak =
                (h1 + h2 + d) / 2;
            ans = max(ans, (int)peak);
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
	Key Insight
After making all restrictions mutually consistent, each interval between two restricted buildings becomes independent. The highest possible building in that interval is obtained by rising at slope +1 and falling at slope -1, giving:
		peak = (leftHeight + rightHeight + distance) / 2
The answer is the maximum such peak over all intervals.
